<PageShell
  title="Health Insurance for Retirees in Nepal | Visa Guide 2026"
  description="Complete guide to health insurance for retirees in Nepal. Compare international plans with critical medical evacuation coverage, pre-existing options, and age 65+ acceptance in the Himalayas."
  headline="Health Insurance for Retirees in Nepal"
  subheadline="Your guide to comprehensive health coverage in the shadow of the world's highest peaks"
  heroImage="/images/countries/default-hero-bg.png"
  tocItems={tocItems}
  relatedLinks={relatedLinks}
  ctaButtonText="Get Retiree Quotes"
  ctaButtonHref="/go/cigna"
>
  <section id="overview">
    <h2>Overview</h2>
    <p>
      Nepal offers retirees Himalayan majesty, ancient spirituality, and ultra-low costs in one of the world's most dramatic settings. From Kathmandu's medieval temples to Pokhara's lakeside tranquility to views of Everest and Annapurna, Nepal provides experiences found nowhere else. For adventurous retirees seeking meaning and mountains over beaches and comfort, Nepal delivers uniquely.
    </p>
    <p>
      Healthcare in Nepal is limited—the weakest of popular Asian retirement destinations. Kathmandu has basic private hospitals for routine care, but serious conditions absolutely require evacuation to Bangkok, Singapore, or India. This reality makes comprehensive international health insurance with robust evacuation coverage not just important but essential—it's the core protection enabling retirement in Nepal.
    </p>
    <p>
      This guide covers Nepal's visa challenges, healthcare limitations, insurance requirements, evacuation realities, and cost planning for retirement in this challenging but rewarding Himalayan destination.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section id="why-nepal">
    <h2>Why Retirees Choose Nepal</h2>
    <p>
      <strong>Himalayan magnificence</strong> is Nepal's incomparable draw. Views of Everest, Annapurna, and countless 8,000-meter peaks provide daily wonder that no other retirement destination can match. For mountain lovers, Nepal offers a lifetime of exploration and inspiration.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Spiritual depth</strong> attracts seekers beyond physical beauty. Buddhist and Hindu traditions permeate daily life. Temples, stupas, meditation retreats, and yoga centers offer genuine spiritual engagement. For retirees seeking inner exploration alongside outer adventure, Nepal provides unmatched opportunity.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Ultra-low costs</strong> enable comfortable retirement on minimal income. A couple can live well for $800-1,200/month including health insurance. Nepal is among the world's cheapest comfortable retirement destinations—stretching even modest fixed income into genuine quality of life.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Trekking paradise</strong> suits active retirees. Countless trails from gentle walks to challenging high-altitude treks provide lifelong exploration. Even non-trekkers enjoy accessible mountain views from Pokhara and other lowland locations.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Warm hospitality</strong> welcomes visitors genuinely. Nepali culture is famously friendly and tolerant. Foreigners are treated with curiosity and kindness. The trekking industry has created English-speaking infrastructure throughout tourist areas.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Pokhara's appeal</strong> provides a gentler Nepal experience. This lakeside town offers Himalayan views without Kathmandu's chaos, established tourist infrastructure, and a relaxed atmosphere popular with long-term visitors and retirees.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section id="visa-options">
    <h2>Visa Options</h2>
    <p>
      Nepal has no dedicated retirement visa, and long-term residence is challenging. Most foreign retirees use tourist visa extensions and periodic exits—not ideal but workable.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Tourist visa:</strong> Available for 15, 30, or 90 days initially. Extensions available at the Department of Immigration in Kathmandu up to a total of 150 days per calendar year. After 150 days, you must leave Nepal. This limit forces periodic exits to India or Thailand.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Non-tourist visas:</strong> Business, student, or work visas allow longer stays but require specific purposes. Some retirees establish small businesses, NGO involvement, or study programs to qualify for non-tourist categories. Complex and not guaranteed.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Retirement reality:</strong> Nepal doesn't actively court retirees the way Thailand, Malaysia, or Panama do. The 150-day annual limit forces visa runs to India (easy overland crossing) or flights to Bangkok. Many retirees accept this rhythm, spending part of the year elsewhere.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Health insurance:</strong> Not legally required but absolutely essential given Nepal's healthcare limitations. Don't even consider Nepal without comprehensive international coverage including robust evacuation benefits. This isn't optional—it's survival planning.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Practical approach:</strong> Most retirees spend 4-5 months in Nepal, exit to India or Thailand, return for another stint. Some split time between Nepal (trekking season) and other destinations (monsoon season June-September is less pleasant anyway).
    </p>
  </section>

  <CTABox
    title="Get Quotes for Nepal Coverage"
    description="Compare international health insurance plans with critical medical evacuation coverage—absolutely essential given Nepal's healthcare limitations."
    buttonText="Compare Plans"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna"
  />

  <section id="insurance-options">
    <h2>Insurance Options for Retirees</h2>
    <p>
      Nepal's healthcare limitations make insurance strategy simple: you need robust international coverage with strong evacuation benefits. There's no combination strategy here—international insurance is the only viable option.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>International health insurance</strong> is absolutely essential. Prioritize plans with evacuation coverage of $500,000 minimum (unlimited is better), coverage in Bangkok and India where evacuation typically goes, and established protocols for high-altitude and remote area evacuations.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Evacuation is the core benefit.</strong> Kathmandu's hospitals handle minor issues, but cardiac events, strokes, serious trauma, complex surgery, and most serious conditions require evacuation. Bangkok (3 hours by air) is the most common destination—excellent hospitals at reasonable cost. Delhi and other Indian cities are alternatives.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>High-altitude coverage:</strong> If you plan trekking above 3,000 meters, verify your policy covers high-altitude emergencies including helicopter rescue. Some policies exclude or limit high-altitude coverage. This is critical in Nepal where altitude-related emergencies are common.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Nepali local insurance</strong> exists but is inadequate for foreign retirees. Local plans provide access to limited local facilities but can't solve the fundamental problem of Nepal's healthcare inadequacy. Don't rely on local coverage.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Adventure sports coverage:</strong> If you plan trekking, paragliding, rafting, or other adventure activities, verify coverage. Many standard policies exclude adventure sports. Nepal-specific coverage additions or adventure-focused policies may be needed.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section id="recommended-providers">
    <h2>Recommended Insurance Providers</h2>
    <p>
      These international insurers provide comprehensive coverage for Nepal retirees with established evacuation networks—the most critical feature for this destination.
    </p>
    <ComparisonTable columns={providerColumns} rows={providerRows} />
    <p>
      <strong>Cigna Global</strong> offers extensive evacuation coverage ($1M+) with established protocols for Nepal. Their network includes Bangkok and Indian hospitals—common evacuation destinations. Moratorium underwriting helps those with pre-existing conditions.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>IMG Global</strong> provides competitive pricing with adequate evacuation coverage. Good choice for budget-conscious retirees who still need robust protection. Verify high-altitude and adventure coverage if needed.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Aetna International</strong> offers unlimited evacuation—valuable peace of mind in Nepal where evacuations can be complex and expensive, especially from remote areas. Strong regional network including Bangkok and India.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Allianz Care</strong> provides comprehensive coverage with unlimited evacuation. Good choice for those wanting established European insurer with strong Asian operations.
    </p>
  </section>

  <CTABox
    title="Compare Retiree Plans for Nepal"
    description="Get personalized quotes from insurers with established Nepal evacuation protocols. Coverage that gets you to Bangkok or Delhi when needed—essential here."
    buttonText="Get Free Quotes"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna"
