  <section id="healthcare-system">
    <h2>Healthcare System Overview</h2>
    <p>
      Nepal's healthcare is limited—the weakest among popular Asian destinations. Understanding these limitations is essential for realistic planning and survival.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Kathmandu hospitals</strong> including Grande International Hospital, Norvic International Hospital, and CIWEC Clinic provide basic care. These facilities can handle minor surgery, routine conditions, and basic emergencies. CIWEC specifically serves foreign visitors with English-speaking staff and evacuation coordination.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Outside Kathmandu,</strong> capabilities are minimal. Pokhara has basic hospitals adequate for minor issues, but serious conditions require Kathmandu or evacuation. Trekking regions have essentially no medical facilities—evacuation by helicopter to Kathmandu, then onward, is the plan for any serious condition.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>What requires evacuation:</strong> Cardiac emergencies, strokes, serious trauma, complex surgery, cancer treatment, and most conditions beyond basic care. Assume evacuation for anything serious. Bangkok's Bumrungrad Hospital is often the destination—world-class care, reasonable cost, established Nepal evacuation protocols.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Altitude emergencies:</strong> Altitude sickness, HACE (high-altitude cerebral edema), and HAPE (high-altitude pulmonary edema) are real risks for trekkers. Helicopter evacuation to lower altitude is the treatment. Your insurance must cover this specifically.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Prescription medications:</strong> Basic medications are available in Kathmandu pharmacies. Selection is limited. Quality can be variable. Specialty medications may be unavailable. Bring supplies of critical medications and maintain buffer stock.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section id="costs">
    <h2>Cost Planning</h2>
    <p>
      Nepal offers extraordinary value—among the world's cheapest retirement destinations. Currency is the Nepali rupee (NPR), pegged to the Indian rupee.
    </p>
    <ComparisonTable columns={costColumns} rows={costRows} />
    <p>
      <strong>Total monthly budget</strong> for comfortable retirement with comprehensive health coverage typically ranges from $900-1,500 depending on location and lifestyle. Kathmandu comfortable retirement runs $1,100-1,500; Pokhara $950-1,300; smaller towns $700-1,000.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Healthcare cost reality:</strong> International insurance costs $230-500/month—proportionally significant given Nepal's ultra-low other costs. Don't skimp because everything else is cheap. Robust evacuation coverage is literally life-saving in Nepal's healthcare environment.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Visa run costs:</strong> Budget $500-1,000 annually for required exits to India or Thailand. These trips can be enjoyable—India is accessible overland, Bangkok by air. Factor this into annual planning given the 150-day annual limit.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Trekking costs:</strong> If you plan trekking, budget for permits, guides (recommended), and gear. Organized treks cost $50-150/day depending on region and services. Independent trekking is cheaper but requires more preparation.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section id="faqs">
    <h2>Common Questions</h2>

    <div class="grid gap-6 md:grid-cols-2 mt-6">
      <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-neutral-200 p-6">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Is Nepal safe?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-700">Generally yes—crime against foreigners is rare. Political protests occasionally occur but rarely affect tourists. Natural disasters (earthquakes, monsoon flooding) are real risks. Trekking has inherent risks. Most retirees report feeling safe in populated areas.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-neutral-200 p-6">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Can older retirees handle Nepal's altitude and terrain?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-700">Depends on fitness and health. Kathmandu (1,400m) and Pokhara (800m) are comfortable altitudes. High-altitude trekking requires good health and acclimatization. Many older people enjoy Nepal without trekking—the culture and views are accessible at lower altitudes.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-neutral-200 p-6">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">How bad is the 150-day visa limit?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-700">Manageable but annoying. You must plan exits—India overland is easy, Bangkok by air is common. Many retirees accept splitting time between Nepal and other destinations. Not ideal for those wanting to stay year-round in one place.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-neutral-200 p-6">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">How good is English in Nepal?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-700">Good in tourist areas—trekking industry has created English-speaking infrastructure. Kathmandu and Pokhara work well in English. Rural areas may require basic Nepali. Healthcare at foreigner-focused clinics (CIWEC) is English-medium.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-neutral-200 p-6">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">What about Kathmandu's pollution and chaos?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-700">Kathmandu is polluted and chaotic—genuinely challenging. Many retirees prefer Pokhara's calmer atmosphere. If you need Kathmandu for healthcare access, consider living in quieter neighborhoods or accepting periodic Pokhara escapes.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-neutral-200 p-6">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Is Nepal suitable for those with health conditions?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-700">Risky. Healthcare limitations make Nepal challenging for those with ongoing complex health needs. Cardiac conditions, cancer requiring monitoring, and other serious conditions may be better managed elsewhere. Consider Nepal only if your health is stable and you accept evacuation as your backup plan.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <CTABox
    title="Ready to Plan Your Nepal Retirement?"
    description="Get personalized quotes from insurers with established Nepal evacuation protocols. Coverage that makes Himalayan retirement possible safely."
    buttonText="Get Your Quotes"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna"
  />
</PageShell>
